<subSubSection id="7460E84A3101EA2791D0BE93598050C1" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" type="description">
<paragraph id="0A46B6E8E1E00092E2B68F20914CE562" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3EDF6A16296FCF842C525DD13AA347EE" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">
Mycelium covering the host, white to cream fluffy, light greyish-brown to violaceous-brown when dried. Synnema multiple, cylindrical, growing from abdomen of host spider, cream to yellowish-white. Conidiophores, (19-) 60-153.5 (-170) 
<normalizedToken id="844617F6BDE2C7A9B39E257C7C44FAAE" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
8-10 
<normalizedToken id="80AAD551C549C8BCF609061BB41B2F47" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation id="437843A407B94BA7CE41D35642A871F9" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Gibellula longispora sp. nov. a, b fungus on a spider c, d conidiophores showing conidial head e part of conidiophore showing rough walls f, g conidial head h conidia. Scale bars: 50 μm (c, d); 20 μm (e), 10 μm (f, g, h)." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.90.83801.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/691582" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">2d</figureCitation>
), crowded, lately arising from hyphae loosely attached to the surface of the synnema, verrucose, multiseptate, suddenly narrowing to a tip, then forming a globose vesicle, (5.5-) 6-8.5 (-9.5) 
<normalizedToken id="98C29F376B708585103CDAA3D749C68E" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
(5-) 5.5-8μm (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="F58D657E960A3832E954D0422708F288" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Gibellula longispora sp. nov. a, b fungus on a spider c, d conidiophores showing conidial head e part of conidiophore showing rough walls f, g conidial head h conidia. Scale bars: 50 μm (c, d); 20 μm (e), 10 μm (f, g, h)." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.90.83801.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/691582" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">2c, f</figureCitation>
). Spherical conidial heads consisting of vesicle, metulae and phialide, (25.5-) 38.5-49 (-50) 
<normalizedToken id="68B8E1E855264D91A25C0A00C596B56B" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
(24.5) 36-46.5 (-49) 
<normalizedToken id="D6399B39EA2FC24DD3BB5728C11FDEE4" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
. A number of broadly obovate to oval metulae, 6.5-9.5 
<normalizedToken id="B8C99404726A7D4BC6BA0A90361570FC" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
(4.5-)5-7 
<normalizedToken id="03955E51AD2F583212D0FF6C7CE34B36" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation id="117768E52886EA912F0A8C8615695A8E" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Gibellula longispora sp. nov. a, b fungus on a spider c, d conidiophores showing conidial head e part of conidiophore showing rough walls f, g conidial head h conidia. Scale bars: 50 μm (c, d); 20 μm (e), 10 μm (f, g, h)." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.90.83801.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/691582" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">2c</figureCitation>
), borne on vesicle, each metulae bearing several clavate phialides, (6.5-) 7-9.5 (-11) 
<normalizedToken id="F06B96578A1D0CD9C61283F628B0CB57" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
(1.5-) 2-3 
<normalizedToken id="28D3B8D989F5724C80CFD46F07618F4F" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation id="5D122ED18479783915ACD731C7C68393" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Gibellula longispora sp. nov. a, b fungus on a spider c, d conidiophores showing conidial head e part of conidiophore showing rough walls f, g conidial head h conidia. Scale bars: 50 μm (c, d); 20 μm (e), 10 μm (f, g, h)." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.90.83801.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/691582" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">2c, f</figureCitation>
). Conidia, 5-7 
<normalizedToken id="CF89FD90D542B1C437289885B388F56D" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1-2 
<normalizedToken id="99D1088545D66CC905A933557BE86639" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation id="9A0277C0A29B9527426375BE7FA79D1A" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Gibellula longispora sp. nov. a, b fungus on a spider c, d conidiophores showing conidial head e part of conidiophore showing rough walls f, g conidial head h conidia. Scale bars: 50 μm (c, d); 20 μm (e), 10 μm (f, g, h)." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.90.83801.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/691582" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">2g</figureCitation>
), narrowly fusiform. Teleomorph and granulomanus synanamorphs not observed. (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="8CA7A55153E0F7C90BED7A9715511FB4" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Gibellula longispora sp. nov. a, b fungus on a spider c, d conidiophores showing conidial head e part of conidiophore showing rough walls f, g conidial head h conidia. Scale bars: 50 μm (c, d); 20 μm (e), 10 μm (f, g, h)." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.90.83801.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/691582" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">2f</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
